elgado assembles a cast of characters to discuss such urgent and timely topics as race, terrorism, hate speech, interracial relationships, freedom of speech, and new theories on civil rights stemming from the most recent war.In the course of this new narrative, Delgado provides analytical breakthroughs, offering new civil rights theories, new approaches to interracial romance and solidarity, and a fresh analysis of how whiteness and white privilege figure into the debate on affirmative action. The characters also discuss the black/white binary paradigm of race and show why it persists even at a time when the country's population is rapidly diversifying.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxCivil rightszUnited States. 0aIntellectualsvFiction. 0aMinoritiesxCivil rightszUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aRace discriminationzUnited States. 0aRacismzUnited States. 7aLAW / Civil Law.2bisacsh1 aHochschild, Jennifer L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHochschild, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081471955840uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814721179.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814721179423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814721179/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL